<span class="displaytext">arlington, va -- today, in florida, (candidate full) once again demonstrated that his words really don't matter. when discussing nasa programs, (candidate full) said that "it's still being reported" that he would delay the nasa constellation program to pay for his early education program. unfortunately for (candidate full), that is what he proposed and has been saying for months: <b><u> </u></b><p>(candidate full): "it's still being reported"...  </p><p>(candidate full) said "it's still being reported that we were talking about delaying some aspects of the constellation program to pay for our early education program." (candidate last): "i mentioned this earlier, i want to tell you that, you know, i know it's still being reported that we were talking about delaying some aspects of the constellation program to pay for our early education program. i told my staff we're going to find an entirely different offset, because we've got to make sure that the money that's going into nasa for basic research and development continues to go there. that has been a top priority for us." ((candidate full), remarks, titusville, fl, 8/208 <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=msxghyj693a"><b><u> <ul> <li></li></ul></u></b></a><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=msxghyj693a">watch </a><b> (candidate full). <u> </u></b></p><p>words matter: (candidate full) said he would pay for his early education program by delaying the nasa constellation program...  </p><p>according to the early education program plan on his own website, (candidate full) pays for his program by in part delaying the nasa constellation program. "the early education plan will be paid for by delaying the nasa constellation program for five years, using purchase cards and the negotiating power of the government to reduce costs of standardized procurement, auctioning surplus federal property, and reducing the erroneous payments identified by the government accountability office, and closing the ceo pay deductibility loophole. the rest of the plan will be funded using a small portion of the savings associated with fighting the war in iraq." ((candidate last) for america, "(candidate full)'s plan for lifetime success through education," <a href="http://(candidate last).3cdn.net/a8dfc36246b3dcc3cb_iem6bxpgh.pdf"><u> www.(candidate full).com</u> </a> , 11/20/07) <b> <ul> <li>in november, (candidate full) proposed cutting nasa's budget to fund his education programs.</li></ul></b> "to pay for his education program, (candidate last) would eliminate tax-deductibility of ceo pay by corporations and delay nasa's program to return to the moon and then journey to mars. (martha t. moore, "(candidate last)'s education plan includes new standards," <i>usa today</i>, 11/21/2007)<b><i> <li>houston chronicle</li></i>: (candidate full)'s proposals to delay space programs would hurt the houston area. </b>"houston is home to the johnson space center. (candidate last) has said he wants to postpone nasa's constellation program for five years. should that happen, the gap between the end of the shuttle program and flight testing of a new spacecraft would exceed 10 years -- years with no u.s. ability to fly humans in space. would (candidate last) really force such a gap, deterring americans from pursuing careers in space science and crippling the u.s. space program for a generation?" (editorial, "how would (candidate full)'s positions affect houston and its residents," <i>houston chronicle</i>, 7/31/08)<b> </b></p><p>today, in an interview with <i>the orlando sentinel</i>, (candidate full) also criticized the constellation program. (candidate full): "i think the constellation project is a bold vision but we haven't thought through all the steps to get there and what the funding sources are." ((candidate full), interview with <i>the orlando sentinel</i>, 8/2/08)</p></span>



